### Top-Level Statements in C#

Introduced in C# 9, top-level statements allow you to write executable code directly without wrapping it in a class or Main method.

### Before and After

**Traditional approach (C# 1-8):**

```csharp
using System;

namespace MyApp
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Hello, World!");
        }
    }
}
```

**Top-level statements (C# 9+):**

```csharp
using System;

Console.WriteLine("Hello, World!");
```

### Key Features

```csharp
using System;
using System.Net.Http;

// Top-level statements - no class or Main needed
Console.WriteLine("Application starting...");

// Variables at global scope
string name = "Alice";
Console.WriteLine($"Hello, {name}");

// Can use await directly
using var client = new HttpClient();
string result = await client.GetStringAsync("https://example.com");
Console.WriteLine($"Downloaded {result.Length} characters");

// Local functions still work
static int Add(int a, int b) => a + b;
Console.WriteLine(Add(5, 3));
```

### Accessing Command-Line Arguments

```csharp
// args is available automatically
if (args.Length > 0)
    Console.WriteLine($"Arguments: {string.Join(", ", args)}");
```

### Async Top-Level Statements

```csharp
// No need for async Task Main
Console.WriteLine("Starting async work...");

await Task.Delay(1000);

Console.WriteLine("Done!");
```

### Return Value

```csharp
// Return an exit code
Console.WriteLine("Processing...");
return 0;  // Exit code
```

### Namespaces and Classes Still Work

```csharp
using System;

Console.WriteLine("From top-level");

namespace MyApp
{
    class Helper
    {
        public static void DoSomething() => Console.WriteLine("From Helper class");
    }
}

MyApp.Helper.DoSomething();
```

### Rules and Limitations

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| One file | Only one file with top-level statements |
| Must come first | Before any type declarations in the file |
| Cannot be in namespace | Not inside a namespace block |
| Implicit Main | Compiler generates a Main method |
| Using directives | Must be at the top, before statements |

### Best Practices

| Use Case | Recommendation |
|----------|---------------|
| Simple programs | Great for scripts, demos, tutorials |
| Utility tools | Quick console tools |
| Production apps | Use for Program.cs entry point |
| Complex apps | Traditional class structure better |

> **Key Point:** Top-level statements simplify the entry point of C# applications. They are ideal for simple programs, scripts, and tutorials. For complex applications, keep the entry point concise and delegate to other classes. Only one file can use top-level statements.

### Limitations

```csharp
// Cannot have top-level statements in:
// - Class libraries
// - WinForms/WPF entry points (still require [STAThread])
// - Multiple files in same project

// Still need traditional Main for:
// - Multiple entry points
// - Custom Main method signature
```

### Generated Main Method

The compiler generates something similar to:

```csharp
static class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        // Your top-level statements
    }
}

